    "boxscore_url": "https://www.charlotte49ers.com/sports/baseball/stats/2026/wichita-state/boxscore/19758",
    "recap_url": "https://www.charlotte49ers.com/news/2026/3/21/baseball-stricklin-matches-rbi-record-as-charlotte-wallops-wichita-state",
    "recap_headline": "Charlotte",
    "recap_text": "WICHITA, Kan. \u2013\nFor the second time this season, a Charlotte baseball player totaled nine RBIs in a single game as\nCale Stricklin\nmatched the program record in a 19-6 win over Wichita State on Saturday afternoon (March 21).\nStricklin hit two homers in the game, the first of his collegiate career \u2013 including a grand slam \u2013 to equal the program record set by\nAlec DeMartino\nearlier this month at Campbell.\nThe win pulls Charlotte (15-8, 1-1 American) level with Wichita State (16-9, 1-1 American) in the weekend series, setting up a rubber match on Sunday.\nStricklin's two home runs were part of a four-hit game for the catcher, making him one of five 49ers with four hits in the game. DeMartino also had a four-hit performance, as did\nCody Gunderson\n,\nDylan Koontz\n, and\nAdrian Jimenez\n. Stricklin, Koontz, and Jimenez all established career-highs with four hits in the game while DeMartino and Gunderson matched their career benchmarks.\nKoontz's four hits also came with a career-high six RBIs thanks to a pair of home runs for his first multi-homer game.\nRobert Nedry\nhad a pair of hits in the win while\nSpencer Nolan\nand\nDawson Bryce\nboth had one for a total of 24 as a team for the Green and White \u2013 the most hits in a single game since racking up 26 knocks against Western Illinois in 2022. The 19 runs scored are also a season high for Charlotte and the most since scoring 20 in the final series of the regular season last year at Tulane.\nThe Niners' five home runs hit in the game are the most this season and the most since hitting five against Memphis in 2024 \u2013 with the final three in that contest being back-to-back-to-back solo shots to open the ninth and walk the game off.\nCharlotte relied on just two arms in the game, with\nDrew Munn\ngetting the start while\nJoseph Taylor\nnotched his team-leading fourth win in relief. Munn went the first 3.1 innings before Taylor finished out the final 5.2, with the duo combining for four strikeouts.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nBoth sides matched each other blow-for-blow early on, getting through the first three innings with each side having one hit per frame.\nCharlotte had the first quality scoring chance in the fourth, loading them up after a pair of singles and a walk, but a ground ball to the pitcher induced a 1-2-3 double play to get the Shockers out of the inning.\nWichita State (16-9, 1-1 American) broke through in the home half of the fourth, bringing four runs around on five hits and a pair of Charlotte errors to open a 4-0 advantage.\nThe Niners didn't trail for long, immediately tying things up with a four-spot of their own in the fifth. Stricklin got the scoring started with a double off the top of the wall in center to bring home Jimenez from first after an infield single. Hudson drew a four-pitch walk with one gone to put a pair on for Koontz, who took one for a ride over the wall in center in almost the same spot as Stricklin's double to level things at four apiece.\nCharlotte continued its offensive attack in the next inning, taking the lead on a two-run single from Stricklin. Bryce was hit by a pitch to get a runner aboard with one out until Jimenez doubled to the gap in right to put both runners in scoring position. Wichita State moved the infield in on Stricklin with only one out and he laced one past the diving third baseman.\nWichita State got one of the runs back to pull within one in the home half of the sixth, scoring without recording a hit after a pair of walks, a sacrifice bunt, and an RBI-groundout.\nThe Niners pushed into double digits before the stretch in the seventh after Koontz and Stricklin both left the yard. Koontz smoked a two-run shot into the parking lot after Gunderson singled before CLT worked them loaded. DeMartino singled after Koontz's second big fly but was retired on a fielder's choice that allowed Nedry to reach. Bryce reached on a bunt single and then Jimenez drew a walk to load them for Stricklin. The single for Bryce kept his hitting streak alive at 16 straight games, the longest of his career and longest of the season for the Green and White.\nStricklin swung at the first pitch he saw and belted one over the wall in left for a grand slam, the team's fifth of the season, and his first collegiate homer.\nCharlotte was held scoreless eighth before Wichita hit a lead-off homer in the home half for the Shockers' final run of the game. That sent it into the ninth, where the Niners did their most damage of the game with a seven-spot.\nNedry began the final frame by taking the new pitcher from the Wichita State bullpen deep to right. Jimenez singled with one out, setting up the record-tying homer from Stricklin to left for his eighth and ninth runs driven in during the game to make it 15-6. Nolan singled one batter later and came home when Gunderson found the wall in left-center with two gone. Gunderson scored one pitch later on a single to right from Koontz, who came home after DeMartino tripled off the top of the wall in center. Nedry batted for the second time in the inning with DeMartino sitting 90 feet away and the former brought him home with an infield single to cap off the runs for the game.\nTaylor returned to the hill with a 13-run lead in his back pocket and got the final two outs of the game on strikes to strand a pair of Shockers on base.\nUP NEXT\nThe two sides will play for the series in the rubber match on Sunday (March 22) at 1 p.m. ET.",
